SIMPLE: serve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Serve
<hw>Serve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Served</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Serving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>serven</ets>,
<ets>servien</ets>, OF. & F. <ets>servir</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>servire</ets>; akin to <ets>servus</ets> a servant or slave,
<ets>servare</ets> to protect, preserve, observe; cf. Zend
<ets>har</ets> to protect, <ets>haurva</ets> protecting. Cf.
<er>Conserve</er>, <er>Desert</er> merit, <er>Dessert</er>,
<er>Observe</er>, <er>Serf</er>, <er>Sergeant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To work for; to labor in behalf of; to exert one's self
continuously or statedly for the benefit of; to do service for; to be in
the employment of, as an inferior, domestic, serf, slave, hired
assistant, official helper, etc.; specifically, in a religious sense, to
obey and worship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God is my witness, whom I <qex>serve</qex> with my spirit.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. i. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jacob loved Rachel; and said, I will <qex>serve</qex> thee seven
years for Rachel thy younger daughter.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxix.
18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No man can <qex>serve</qex> two masters.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vi.
24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had I but <qex>served</qex> my God with half the zeal⟦br⟧
I <qex>served</qex> my king, he would not in mine age⟦br⟧
Have left me naked to mine enemies.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be subordinate to; to act a secondary part under;
to appear as the inferior of; to minister to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bodies bright and greater should not <qex>serve</qex>⟦br⟧
The less not bright.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be suitor to; to profess love to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>serve</qex> a lady in his beste wise.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To wait upon; to supply the wants of; to attend;
specifically, to wait upon at table; to attend at meals; to supply with
food; <as>as, to <ex>serve</ex> customers in a shop</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Others, pampered in their shameless pride,⟦br⟧
Are <qex>served</qex> in plate and in their chariots ride.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Hence, to bring forward, arrange, deal, or
distribute, as a portion of anything, especially of food prepared for
eating; -- often with <xex>up</xex>; formerly with
<xex>in</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bid them cover the table, <qex>serve</qex> in the meat, and we
will come in to dinner.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some part he roasts, then <qex>serves</qex> it up so dressed.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryde.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1316 --></p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To perform the duties belonging to, or required in
or for; hence, to be of use to; <as>as, a curate may <ex>serve</ex> two
churches; to <ex>serve</ex> one's country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To contribute or conduce to; to promote; to be
sufficient for; to satisfy; <as>as, to <ex>serve</ex> one's
turn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Turn it into some advantage, by observing where it can
<qex>serve</qex> another end.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To answer or be (in the place of something) to;
<as>as, a sofa <ex>serves</ex> one for a seat and a
couch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To treat; to behave one's self to; to requite; to
act toward; <as>as, he <ex>served</ex> me very ill</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To work; to operate; <as>as, to <ex>serve</ex> the
guns</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To bring to notice,
deliver, or execute, either actually or constructively, in such manner
as the law requires; <as>as, to <ex>serve</ex> a summons</as>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>To make legal service opon (a person named in a writ,
summons, etc.); <as>as, to <ex>serve</ex> a witness with a
subp⟦oe⟧na</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To pass or spend, as time, esp. time of punishment;
<as>as, to <ex>serve</ex> a term in prison</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To copulate with; to cover; <as>as, a horse
<ex>serves</ex> a mare</as>; -- said of the male.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Tennis)</fld> <def>To lead off in delivering (the
ball).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To wind spun yarn, or the like,
tightly around (a rope or cable, etc.) so as to protect it from chafing
or from the weather. See under <er>Serving</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>To serve an attachment</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>To serve a writ of attachment</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<cd>to levy it on the person or goods by seizure, or to seize.</cd> --
<col><b>To serve an execution</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to levy it
on a lands, goods, or person, by seizure or taking possession.</cd> --
<col><b>To serve an office</b></col>, <cd>to discharge a public
duty.</cd> -- <col><b>To serve a process</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<cd>in general, to read it, so as to give due notice to the party
concerned, or to leave an attested copy with him or his attorney, or his
usual place of abode.</cd> -- <col><b>To serve a warrant</b></col>,
<cd>to read it, and seize the person against whom it is issued.</cd> --
<col><b>To serve a writ</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to read it to
the defendant, or to leave an attested copy at his usual place of
abode.</cd> -- <col><b>To serve one out</b></col>, <cd>to retaliate
upon; to requite.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I'll <xex>serve you out</xex> for
this.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>C. Kingsley.</au> -- <col><b>To serve one
right</b></col>, <cd>to treat, or cause to befall one, according to his
deserts; -- used commonly of ill deserts; <as>as, it <ex>serves</ex> the
scoundrel <ex>right</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To serve one's self
of</b></col>, <cd>to avail one's self of; to make use of.</cd> <mark>[A
Gallicism]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>serve myself of</qex> this concession.</q>
<rj><qau>Chillingworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p> -- <col><b>To serve out</b></col>, <cd>to distribute; <as>as, <ex>to
serve out</ex> rations</as>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To serve the
time</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To serve the hour</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>to regulate one's actions by the requirements of the time instead of
by one's duty; to be a timeserver.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They think herein we <qex>serve the time</qex>, because thereby we
either hold or seek preferment.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>
⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To obey; minister to; subserve; promote; aid;
help; assist; benefit; succor.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Serve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Serve
<hw>Serve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be a
servant or a slave; to be employed in labor or other business for
another; to be in subjection or bondage; to render menial
service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord shall give thee rest . . . from the hard bondage wherein
thou wast made to <qex>serve</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xiv.
3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perform domestic offices; to be occupied with
household affairs; to prepare and dish up food, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But Martha . . . said, Lord, dost thou not care that my sister
hath left me to <qex>serve</qex> alone?</q> <rj><qau>Luke x.
40.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be in service; to do duty; to discharge the
requirements of an office or employment. Specifically, to act in the
public service, as a soldier, seaman. etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many . . . who had before been great commanders, but now
<qex>served</qex> as private gentlemen without pay.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be of use; to answer a purpose; to suffice; to
suit; to be convenient or favorable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This little brand will <qex>serve</qex> to light your fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As occasion <qex>serves</qex>, this noble queen⟦br⟧
And prince shall follow with a fresh supply.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Tennis)</fld> <def>To lead off in delivering the
ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Server</ent>⟦br⟧
